e demonstrates how gender inequality is both constructed and contested in professional sport. Allison details the complex constructions of race, class, gender, and sexuality in the selling and marketing of women’s soccer in a half-changed sports landscape characterized by both progress and backlash, and where professional sports are still understood to be men’s territory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSoccer for womenxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSoccer for womenzUnited States. 0aSoccerxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomen soccer playerszUnited States. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh  aWomen's National Team.  adisparities.  agender.  agirls.  ainequality.  aprofessional.  asoccer.  asports.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081358679340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813586793423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813586793.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK